# Day 14 – Linux Services Troubleshooting: Apache Service Recovery

## 📌 Project Overview

On Day 14 of my **#100DaysOfDevOps** challenge, I worked on a real-world Linux troubleshooting scenario involving the Apache HTTP Server. 
A monitoring system detected that the Apache service was unavailable on one of the application servers within a multi-server infrastructure.

The objective was to identify the faulty server, restore the Apache service, and ensure that all application servers were consistently configured to listen on **port 3004**.

---

## 🎯 Objectives

* Identify the application server with the failed Apache service.
* Diagnose the root cause of the failure.
* Restore the Apache service.
* Configure Apache to listen on port **3004**.
* Verify that Apache is active and running on every application server.

---

## 🏗️ Environment

* Linux Application Servers (stapp01, stapp02, stapp03)
* Apache HTTP Server (httpd)
* SSH for remote administration
* Systemd service management

---

## 🔍 Problem Statement

The production monitoring system reported that Apache was unavailable on one of the application servers.

Requirements:

* Apache must be running on all application servers.
* Apache must listen on **port 3004**.
* No web application deployment was required; only service availability needed to be restored.

---

## 🛠️ Troubleshooting Process

### 1. Connected to Each Application Server

SSH was used to access every application server individually.

```bash
ssh tony@stapp01
ssh tony@stapp02
ssh tony@stapp03
```

---

### 2. Verified Apache Service Status

Checked the status of the Apache service to identify the unhealthy server.

```bash
sudo systemctl status httpd
```

This immediately revealed which server had the failed service.

---

### 3. Investigated the Failure

Reviewed the service status and system logs to determine why Apache failed to start.

```bash
sudo journalctl -xeu httpd
```

Service logs are one of the most valuable resources during Linux troubleshooting because they provide the exact reason a service failed.

---

### 4. Validated Apache Configuration

Before restarting the service, the Apache configuration was validated.

```bash
sudo httpd -t
```

Expected output:

```
Syntax OK
```

Configuration validation helps prevent repeated service failures caused by syntax errors.

---

### 5. Verified Apache Listening Port

Checked the Apache configuration file to ensure the service was configured to listen on the required port.

```bash
grep Listen /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf
```

Expected configuration:

```
Listen 3004
```

---

### 6. Restarted Apache

After resolving the issue, Apache was restarted.

```bash
sudo systemctl restart httpd
```

---

### 7. Confirmed Service Health

Verified that Apache was running successfully.

```bash
sudo systemctl status httpd
```

Expected result:

```
Active: active (running)
```

---

### 8. Verified Listening Port

Confirmed that Apache was bound to port **3004**.

```bash
sudo ss -tulnp | grep 3004
```

---

## ✅ Outcome

* Successfully identified the faulty application server.
* Restored the Apache HTTP service.
* Verified Apache configuration.
* Ensured Apache was listening on port **3004**.
* Confirmed the service was running successfully on all application servers.

---

## 💡 Key Takeaways

This project reinforced that effective troubleshooting follows a structured process rather than trial and error. By validating service status, examining logs, testing configuration syntax, and confirming network bindings, I restored service availability while ensuring configuration consistency across multiple servers.

These are the same diagnostic techniques used by DevOps and Site Reliability Engineers (SREs) when responding to production incidents.

